          "title": "The petition: the anatomy of honest suffering",
          "body": "At verse 21 the psalm turns sharply inward. 'But You, O God, the Lord, deal kindly with me for Your name's sake.' The pivot word is *chesed* — the same lovingkindness the enemy refused (v. 16) is now David's only ground of appeal. He does not appeal to his own righteousness or to the justice of his case. He appeals to God's character. The self-description that follows (vv. 22-25) is among the most unsparing in the Psalter: afflicted, needy, heart pierced within him, fading like a late-afternoon shadow, shaken off like a locust, knees weak from fasting, flesh wasted, a reproach whose appearance provokes head-wagging contempt. This is a man with nothing left. Commentators across traditions — Calvin (*Commentary on the Psalms*), Spurgeon (*Treasury of David*), and Kidner — all note that this vulnerability is not weakness but theological honesty. David does not pretend to be stronger than he is. He presents the wreck of himself and asks God to save it. This is the posture of the *evyon* — the destitute one who has no resource but the One who stands at his right hand."
